00:07:36.656 --> 00:07:39.859
But I wanted to maybe transition into one of those

00:07:40.026 --> 00:07:49.001
longer form pieces. You did a great study both in 2024 and then sort of compared that in 2025 across sort of the e-commerce landscape.

00:07:49.001 --> 00:07:53.940
And it's probably very timely sort of moving into PQ4, right?

00:07:53.940 --> 00:08:02.248
So maybe just for the listeners, get an overview of what that study was, and maybe a couple of the key insights that sort of came out of that.

00:08:02.248 --> 00:08:07.086
I found it really interesting and maybe not surprising just in terms of how

00:08:07.086 --> 00:08:08.754
much Google has been changing.

00:08:08.754 --> 00:08:09.155
Thank you.

00:08:09.155 --> 00:08:14.393
I had an opportunity to look at 35,000 queries provided by SEO Clarity

00:08:14.393 --> 00:08:18.831
and focused on the search features that we're seeing for these queries specifically.

00:08:18.831 --> 00:08:23.970
So rather than just looking at who's dominating for these queries in classical organic search

00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:30.343
I was curious what do shopping ads, local packs, product grids, AI overviews, image carousels,

00:08:30.343 --> 00:08:31.878
etcetera, look like over time?

00:08:31.878 --> 00:08:33.646
And what I found is that

00:08:33.646 --> 00:08:36.349
I would probably say there are three bigger realizations.

00:08:36.349 --> 00:08:41.153
One, interestingly, AI overviews are starting to replace product grids.

00:08:41.153 --> 00:08:42.221
Now, I want to be cautious.

00:08:42.221 --> 00:08:44.790
AI overviews are only showing up for fractions still, right?

00:08:44.790 --> 00:08:47.260
This is a small trend that is growing rapidly.

00:08:47.260 --> 00:08:51.864
But you can see that as AI overviews are getting more traction in the search results

00:08:51.864 --> 00:08:54.600
product grids are losing traction.

00:08:54.600 --> 00:08:57.036
And it's a very interesting shift, in my opinion, because...

00:08:57.036 --> 00:08:59.705
Google was very aggressive about showing product grids.

00:08:59.705 --> 00:09:02.575
When I did that analysis the first time in 2024

00:09:02.575 --> 00:09:09.081
I think Google had already shown around 40-ish percent of keywords were showing product grids.

00:09:09.081 --> 00:09:14.520
And I mean, product grids are essentially a different experience of search compared to classical organic results.

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:19.625
It's much more visual grid style way of exploring products.

00:09:19.625 --> 00:09:21.327
And it seems like a year later,

00:09:21.327 --> 00:09:29.702
AI is the dominating kind of vehicle for shopping results, is starting to become the dominating vehicle for shopping results.

00:09:29.702 --> 00:09:31.137
So that was interesting.

00:09:31.137 --> 00:09:38.678
Two, Google has dialed up the number of image carousels so far that this is not the most prominent search feature.

00:09:38.678 --> 00:09:43.749
So if you're thinking about how does Google augment the search results the most, it's with images.

00:09:43.749 --> 00:09:47.620
And again, it kind of makes sense because it's very, very similar to product grids.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.690
The difference might be that when you click on an image you don't get to a product page

00:09:50.690 --> 00:09:53.292
but apart from that, shopping is visual, right?

00:09:53.292 --> 00:09:57.663
And you see that also on TikTok, on Instagram, a little bit on YouTube

00:09:57.663 --> 00:10:03.569
that these platforms are primary discovery drivers in shopping.

00:10:03.569 --> 00:10:10.843
And then maybe as a third surprise to me at least is that the degree of, or the amount of keywords that are showing a discussions

00:10:10.843 --> 00:10:14.213
and forums' search feature is decreasing.

00:10:14.213 --> 00:10:18.084
So we all know that Reddit is one of the largest sites now on the web.

00:10:18.084 --> 00:10:19.585
It's probably in my data,

00:10:19.585 --> 00:10:23.389
it's the second largest site on the web, showing up for all sorts of queries.

00:10:23.389 --> 00:10:27.560
And I noticed that counter to the trend, to the overall trend, in e-commerce

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:33.299
the number of Reddit results, at least for the discussions and forums, search is actually going down.

00:10:33.299 --> 00:10:38.004
So it seems like that in that sense, Google still shows Reddit results, but not anymore

00:10:38.004 --> 00:10:39.739
in this specific pack.

00:10:39.739 --> 00:10:43.843
And so it was interesting to me because my experience observation

00:10:43.843 --> 00:10:46.746
is that people really do want opinions from others when it comes to shopping

00:10:46.746 --> 00:10:50.282
meaning from others that are not affiliates or otherwise incentivized.

00:10:50.282 --> 00:10:51.717
But that seems to be going down for now.

00:10:51.717 --> 00:10:53.919
And maybe it's just a Google test and they ramp it back up.

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:55.588
But that's the data as I see it today.

00:10:55.588 --> 00:10:59.091
It's definitely interesting and it maybe forces folks to think differently 

00:10:59.091 --> 00:11:05.631
when it comes to advertising and making Q4 pushes for Black Friday and Cyber Monday

00:11:05.631 --> 00:11:06.565
those sorts of dates.

00:11:06.565 --> 00:11:11.504
Do you have any thoughts on how your clients should approach something like that

00:11:11.504 --> 00:11:15.107
given how the SERP is changing and modifying.

00:11:15.107 --> 00:11:19.211
Yes, the thing is that these kind of shopping holidays, I mean, they're stretching out
more and more, right?

00:11:19.211 --> 00:11:21.647
Yes, the thing is that these kind of shopping holidays, I mean, they're stretching out
more and more, right?

00:11:21.647 --> 00:11:26.819
There's a lot of data about how BFCM, Black Friday, Ciber Monday, starts earlier and earlier
every year.

00:11:26.819 --> 00:11:34.360
And also last year and probably this year is also a bit tainted by the economic impact on shopping behavior.

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:36.929
It seems that there's some price sensitivity.

00:11:36.929 --> 00:11:40.533
People are looking more for sales and discounts and promotions.

00:11:40.533 --> 00:11:43.035
I mean, it kind of makes sense. The whole holiday is around promotions

00:11:43.035 --> 00:11:48.574
but this year and last year, for sure, people were a lot more sensitive to that than in the previous years.

00:11:48.574 --> 00:11:56.949
And so, my recommendation is to start early with a discount strategy and then try to stretch that over the holidays.

00:11:56.949 --> 00:11:59.018
So don't discount all your products on day one,

00:11:59.018 --> 00:12:02.521
but maybe you want to start in... let's say,

00:12:02.521 --> 00:12:07.660
maybe in October to discount a couple of products. And then maybe every week you have a different category or so

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:11.864
or maybe a featured product that is being discounted as under the umbrella of BFCM.

00:12:11.864 --> 00:12:16.802
You know, according to the data, promoting that across forums is probably less important now.

00:12:16.802 --> 00:12:19.905
Having good visuals for that is probably a little bit more important.

00:12:19.905 --> 00:12:22.341
So, one example is when you have product pages.

00:12:22.341 --> 00:12:24.643
And you typically have a couple of different product images.

00:12:24.643 --> 00:12:29.181
Maybe one of these product images, maybe the preferred one, the main one that people see
first

00:12:29.181 --> 00:12:33.185
Maybe that has, like, a little discount, or promotion or BFCM label on it, right?

00:12:33.185 --> 00:12:35.321
So playing and toying around with that a little bit.

00:12:35.321 --> 00:12:37.723
And then when it comes to AI overviews, I'm pretty sure that

00:12:37.723 --> 00:12:44.029
the searches for products plus Black Friday, Cyber Monday or Black Friday or just Cyber Monday

00:12:44.029 --> 00:12:50.636
you know, these iterations, these BFCM related queries, I'm pretty sure that they're going to start growing

00:12:50.636 --> 00:12:53.105
at the end of September, maybe early October, maybe even earlier.

00:12:53.105 --> 00:12:56.942
And the guidance that I give to my clients is to start monitoring

00:12:56.942 --> 00:13:01.914
where AI are showing up for these types of queries, what they look like. And if you have

00:13:01.914 --> 00:13:05.718
the corresponding content for that, and maybe even coverage on other sites, right?

00:13:05.718 --> 00:13:10.089
So, you definitely want to have at least one landing page for BFCM for every year.

00:13:10.089 --> 00:13:12.591
Not the same one, but a new one every year.

00:13:12.591 --> 00:13:17.062
Maybe you can use some of your backlinks to all the ones to link to the new one, etcetera.

00:13:17.062 --> 00:13:20.833
So that’s some content strategy around BFCM to address AI overviews.

00:13:20.833 --> 00:13:23.469
Yeah, that's probably kind of my strategy in a nutshell for that.

00:13:23.469 --> 00:13:27.273
Got it, I thought that one thing that was sort of interesting about that study

00:13:27.273 --> 00:13:28.974
was the, like you said

00:13:28.974 --> 00:13:34.613
the decrease in maybe discussions, forums, maybe people also ask and things like that,

00:13:34.613 --> 00:13:43.556
 which if we take that to one of your other studies around sort of like LLMs and content
structure is a little bit in conflict, right?

00:13:43.556 --> 00:13:45.724
Because one of the recommendations,

00:13:45.724 --> 00:13:50.629
not just from you, but from others in terms of how LLMs are interpreting that data, right?

00:13:50.629 --> 00:13:54.767
like FAQs and question and answer formats and things like that make a lot of sense.

00:13:54.767 --> 00:13:56.635
So maybe we can jump to that study a little bit.

00:13:56.635 --> 00:13:59.939
So, you know, you looked across a number of different chatbots.

00:13:59.939 --> 00:14:05.444
Maybe take the listeners through some of the key findings across each one of those, that really sort of stood out.

00:14:05.444 --> 00:14:07.847
There's definitely some similarities across all

00:14:07.847 --> 00:14:12.318
but, I think some of the nuances were really interesting to dig into.

00:14:12.318 --> 00:14:12.918
Absolutely.

00:14:12.918 --> 00:14:17.957
So what's interesting is that it turns out that the dominant chatbots rely on

00:14:17.957 --> 00:14:23.963
a very different mix of sources when it comes to how they give their answers.

00:14:23.963 --> 00:14:27.900
So what it means is chatGTP, for example, relies very heavily on Wikipedia.

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:30.402
Perplexity relies a lot more on Reddit.

00:14:30.402 --> 00:14:32.504
Google also relies a lot more on Reddit, right?.

00:14:32.504 --> 00:14:34.640
Perplexity emulates Google a lot

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:39.678
very Google heavy. And then, you know, all the other chatbots from Copilot to Gemini, etc.

00:14:39.678 --> 00:14:45.784
They all have kind of their own mix of sources when it comes to the citations to give answers.

00:14:45.784 --> 00:14:50.689
Which in return means that if you want to optimize for visibility on these chatbots

00:14:50.689 --> 00:14:54.560
you might want to set a different emphasis based on which one is most important to you.

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:59.198
I would say most of my clients see the biggest returns from ChatGPT.

00:14:59.198 --> 00:15:00.733
That seems to be the dominant one.

00:15:00.733 --> 00:15:06.739
It's far ahead of anyone else. When we look at just the traffic going to ChatGPT

00:15:06.739 --> 00:15:10.910
 which I think strongly kind of correlates probably with users.

00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:14.613
And then have Gemini growing the fastest.

00:15:14.613 --> 00:15:16.148
I think they're now in second place

00:15:16.148 --> 00:15:21.987
and then Claude, Grok, Copilot, Perplexity, and DeepSeek and all the others.

00:15:21.987 --> 00:15:24.456
So, most people get the biggest returns from ChatGTP.

00:15:24.456 --> 00:15:26.025
And so what that means is...

00:15:26.025 --> 00:15:27.293
influencing Wikipedia is hard.

00:15:27.293 --> 00:15:31.363
It might be worth a second look just to make sure that as a company

00:15:31.363 --> 00:15:35.534
you're accurately represented, there's no information gap.

00:15:35.534 --> 00:15:39.171
If that's the case, I think it's more than a fair pitch to to try to correct that.

00:15:39.171 --> 00:15:44.176
But again, the Wikipedia defenses are incredibly strong, very strong immune system

00:15:44.176 --> 00:15:47.646
that quickly rejects any attempt to tamper with the pages.

00:15:47.646 --> 00:15:48.881
But it's worth a look and a try.

00:15:48.881 --> 00:15:49.581
After that,

00:15:49.581 --> 00:15:52.685
Reddit has become a lot more impactful when it comes to ChatGPT.

00:15:52.685 --> 00:15:57.222
I used in the beginning there was no visibility at all from Reddit.

00:15:57.222 --> 00:16:00.492
Now, that has jumped up overnight.

00:16:00.492 --> 00:16:01.493
I have to look at the dates again.

00:16:01.493 --> 00:16:04.430
I think it was maybe sometime in May this year.

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:07.833
And it could be due to the partnership that OpenAI has with Reddit

00:16:07.833 --> 00:16:09.568
that it just kind of turned the switch on.

00:16:09.568 --> 00:16:15.407
Now it seems like over 5%, maybe at this point more than citations come from Reddit actually.

00:16:15.407 --> 00:16:16.942
So that now becomes a viable

00:16:16.942 --> 00:16:20.412
optimization platform, but then there's also LinkedIn and YouTube.

00:16:20.412 --> 00:16:23.983
Both of these are, I think, maybe LinkedIn, not in the Black Hat community

00:16:23.983 --> 00:16:32.091
but I think in general they're a little bit overlooked as ways to influence AI answers, right?

00:16:32.091 --> 00:16:35.194
And so things that I'm pushing with my clients is

00:16:35.194 --> 00:16:41.066
for example, to create YouTube videos for specific prompts that were maybe not visible for

00:16:41.066 --> 00:16:42.735
And then LinkedIn, uh what's it called?

00:16:42.735 --> 00:16:49.641
LinkedIn Newsletters or LinkedIn Pulse, I think, is another very popular source with OpenAI.

00:16:49.641 --> 00:16:55.080
And of course, some of that could be questionable because it is used for maybe some shady tactics

00:16:55.080 --> 00:17:03.789
but the reality is that these kind of social content platforms have an outsized impact on ChatGPT.

00:17:03.789 --> 00:17:08.127
And then when comes to software reviews, for example, we have players like G2

00:17:08.127 --> 00:17:09.528
when it comes to health, we have Healthline.

00:17:09.528 --> 00:17:13.699
So every niche, of course, has its predominant citation source

00:17:13.699 --> 00:17:20.005
but overall, anything that is UGC and content-driven has an outsizing impact.

00:17:20.005 --> 00:17:25.577
Yeah, I think it was Lily Ray who showed how easy it was to manipulate

00:17:25.577 --> 00:17:29.782
with a LinkedIn newsletter pulse or whatever they're called

00:17:29.782 --> 00:17:34.019
just to say like, who's the best SEO and that sort of thing.

00:17:34.019 --> 00:17:40.759
The other thing that I saw, which I think aligns really well with this study was someone
totally escaping me.

00:17:40.759 --> 00:17:44.963
But basically, if you monitor perplexities like trending searches,

00:17:44.963 --> 00:17:50.035
 and you can spin up a video really quickly, you'll basically own, you know, that citation.

00:17:50.035 --> 00:17:54.273
So yeah, think the folks who want to, I don't know if spam is the right word

00:17:54.273 --> 00:18:01.413
but manipulate these engines quickly are finding ways to do that relatively easily at this point.

00:18:01.413 --> 00:18:05.517
I think one of the things that was really interesting from the study was who was not

00:18:05.517 --> 00:18:09.688
being included, Like CNET and some of these other really large players

00:18:09.688 --> 00:18:17.362
seem to be mostly related to just blocking the crawlers outright through robots.txt.

00:18:17.362 --> 00:18:19.431
I wanted to, we've had a couple of conversations with guests around this.

00:18:19.431 --> 00:18:22.234
Like what are your, you advise a lot of really big brands.

00:18:22.234 --> 00:18:26.438
What do you, or how do you advise them if they come to you and say

00:18:26.438 --> 00:18:29.908
We really don't want to give our content away for free.

00:18:29.908 --> 00:18:32.744
We're proposing just blocking everything.

00:18:32.744 --> 00:18:35.547
How do you tackle that conversation?

00:18:35.547 --> 00:18:40.185
And maybe just generally, what are your thoughts around companies that are doing that today?

00:18:40.185 --> 00:18:42.154
I can very much empathize with that decision.

00:18:42.154 --> 00:18:46.825
I think the first step is always to do a simple ROI calculation.

00:18:46.825 --> 00:18:52.965
What are we getting today from AI chatbots, but also from Google?

00:18:52.965 --> 00:18:55.701
I think that decision is also on the table.

00:18:56.034 --> 00:18:57.102
And what are we getting?

00:18:57.102 --> 00:18:58.937
uh What are we giving?

00:18:58.937 --> 00:19:01.340
What is the cost to create the content?

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:05.210
What's the risk profile or degree of risk today

00:19:05.210 --> 00:19:10.282
versus the next three years if these trends keep trending the way that they are right now.

00:19:10.282 --> 00:19:12.317
But then also, like, what could we get down the line?

00:19:12.317 --> 00:19:18.857
I haven't published this data yet, but according to SimilarWeb, ChatGPT has been growing by over 700 % year over year.

00:19:18.857 --> 00:19:25.464
So when you compare 25 to 24, you see a 700 % increase in outgoing traffic.

00:19:25.464 --> 00:19:27.132
Does not mean that you're

00:19:27.132 --> 00:19:30.102
traffic will grow by 7x or 8x necessarily.

00:19:30.102 --> 00:19:34.773
But it just means that these AI chatbots seem to be very interested in sending out more traffic.

00:19:34.773 --> 00:19:37.543
And again, new model is just out, ChatGPT 5.

00:19:37.543 --> 00:19:40.245
We need to kind of keep monitoring that trend.

00:19:40.245 --> 00:19:43.315
The point that I'm making is you cannot just look at what you're getting now.

00:19:43.315 --> 00:19:45.417
You have to kind of extrapolate that in the future.

00:19:45.417 --> 00:19:49.888
Are we maybe getting to a significant degree of AI chatbot traffic that could offset

00:19:49.888 --> 00:19:51.857
some of the losses that we're seeing from Google Search

00:19:51.857 --> 00:19:55.127
Because reality is that despite what Google is saying right now

00:19:55.127 --> 00:20:02.234
I still want to see the site that is not losing traffic from AI overviews, I think every site is.

00:20:02.234 --> 00:20:06.038
And sure, you can offset that by just pumping out massive volumes of content.

00:20:06.038 --> 00:20:11.677
So, you don't necessarily lose traffic year over year in absolute terms

00:20:11.677 --> 00:20:13.579
but in relative terms, you absolutely are,

00:20:13.579 --> 00:20:16.048
like what you would have gotten versus what you get today.

00:20:16.048 --> 00:20:17.216
You can make that simple analysis.

00:20:17.216 --> 00:20:20.085
So anyway, coming back to it, before making a decision,

00:20:20.085 --> 00:20:21.787
Cost benefit analysis.

00:20:21.787 --> 00:20:22.521
What are we giving?

00:20:22.521 --> 00:20:23.488
What are we getting?

00:20:23.488 --> 00:20:26.758
What would it look like in the next three to maybe five years?

00:20:26.758 --> 00:20:30.362
And then I think you know, I Think it's more than viable and actually it makes sense

00:20:30.362 --> 00:20:33.865
for a lot of companies to block Google and AI chatbots.

00:20:33.865 --> 00:20:42.341
Just yesterday I saw a tweet from WalletHub saying that they're doing that now and yeah, and and so...

00:20:42.341 --> 00:20:48.614
I predicted that last year that we're going to see lot more companies that are going to
exclude Google and ChatGPT and Co.

00:20:48.614 --> 00:20:51.483
Because for them, it just doesn't make sense anymore.

00:20:51.483 --> 00:20:54.453
And at the front of that trend, we're seeing publishers.

00:20:54.453 --> 00:21:01.760
Makes perfect sense because they're critically dependent on getting clicks for ad traffic, for affiliate traffic.

00:21:01.760 --> 00:21:09.434
Even if you have a subscription model, in most cases, it's not enough to sustain the company, at least in its current form.

00:21:09.434 --> 00:21:11.770
So publishers are at the forefront.

00:21:11.770 --> 00:21:17.242
Affiliates have already been hit really hard and decimated in 2023 by the helpful content updates.

00:21:17.242 --> 00:21:21.513
So if that wouldn't have been the case, then they would probably be staying right next to publishers.

00:21:21.513 --> 00:21:30.355
And so I think any content heavy model, there are also companies like Chegg or Stack Overflow that are also being absolutely obliterated by AI overviews  

00:21:30.355 --> 00:21:32.190
and for these companies, I think it makes sense to say

00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:35.694
Okay, let's look at other traffic channels, other ways to grow the business

00:21:35.694 --> 00:21:38.864
and maybe adopt Cloudflare's paper crawl model.

00:21:38.864 --> 00:21:44.169
So Cloudflare made this really interesting, push into since they govern so much of the web

00:21:44.169 --> 00:21:47.606
and there's such an intermediary between users and search, etc.

00:21:47.606 --> 00:21:54.112
And they released this project called paper crawl where essentially you block bots, and you can be specific about which ones

00:21:54.112 --> 00:22:00.085
from calling and using your content for training data, or for RAG answers, for reasoning.

00:22:00.085 --> 00:22:05.157
Instead, they either need to ask for permission or they need to pay.

00:22:05.157 --> 00:22:08.860
Now, this is to be clear, right? Like you're not getting paid yet.

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:15.000
This is still an attempt to build a big enough pole for then the search engines

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:19.671
and AI developers to come to the table and say, OK, this is going to be a model.

00:22:19.671 --> 00:22:21.173
It makes perfect sense to me, right?

00:22:21.173 --> 00:22:25.243
The economics of the web are deeply in the red for traffic.

00:22:25.243 --> 00:22:29.681
And so I'm not surprised to see more more companies not take on that deal anymore.

00:22:29.681 --> 00:22:33.685
Yeah, I think that's the fundamental challenge of all of this, right?

00:22:33.685 --> 00:22:41.159
Is that there isn't a big enough pool of users or companies sort of demanding for X thing.

00:22:41.159 --> 00:22:45.897
Even when you do have a cohort of people, they may not be all asking for the same things.

00:22:45.897 --> 00:22:49.301
And so you still have this sort of divergence across, I don't know

00:22:49.301 --> 00:22:56.208
the effort to sort of rein this in, and be more cognizant about where they're getting traffic from.

00:22:56.208 --> 00:22:58.243
So I think you're exactly right.

00:22:58.243 --> 00:23:00.712
I thought another thing that was pretty interesting from the study

00:23:00.712 --> 00:23:04.916
was the simplicity of how the content should be created.

00:23:04.916 --> 00:23:07.185
You talk a lot about measuring like flash scores

00:23:07.185 --> 00:23:11.056
and just thinking about like simple sentence structures and things like that.

00:23:11.056 --> 00:23:17.996
I was curious If you wanted to analyze like how simple your content is at scale.

00:23:17.996 --> 00:23:22.834
Is that something that, like, a screaming frog, could help us evaluate from a content perspective?

00:23:22.834 --> 00:23:27.706
Or what sort of tools would you recommend your clients use to sort of evaluate that,

00:23:27.706 --> 00:23:30.509
maybe just to establish a baseline of where you are today?

00:23:30.509 --> 00:23:35.046
Screaming frog is a great option because it allows you to crawl all of your content

00:23:35.046 --> 00:23:39.151
and then determine like the average flash score or complexity

00:23:39.151 --> 00:23:45.223
But there lots of tools from the SEMrush and Ahrefs of the world to keyword insights, Surfer, ClearScope...

00:23:45.223 --> 00:23:49.828
They all give you a sense of how complicated your content is to understand compared to

00:23:49.828 --> 00:23:53.899
what the other very visible articles are showing.

00:23:53.899 --> 00:23:55.500
I think that is one good start.

00:23:55.500 --> 00:23:58.036
I think then also understanding your topic gaps.

00:23:58.036 --> 00:24:04.309
And again, there many ways to get there from building your own topic maps to using some of the tools that I mentioned.

00:24:04.309 --> 00:24:05.744
All of these could help with that.

00:24:05.744 --> 00:24:07.179
But then there are these kind of...

00:24:07.179 --> 00:24:11.950
I think it's like it's an evolution of what we've been doing in SEO for a while

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:15.554
because the reality is that none of these recommendations are really net new.

00:24:15.554 --> 00:24:17.122
They're just sticking out more.

00:24:17.122 --> 00:24:20.559
They're just amplified by AI and AI visibility.

00:24:20.559 --> 00:24:24.563
And so there's a lot to be said about the structure of the content, meaning the way you use headings.

00:24:24.563 --> 00:24:28.366
First of all, you should be using headings if you want to go the extra mile.

00:24:28.366 --> 00:24:29.901
You obviously want to have a clear hierarchy

00:24:29.901 --> 00:24:33.605
you want to have these headings be descriptive and related to the content.

00:24:33.605 --> 00:24:37.209
And I still, all the time, when I just look at headings

00:24:37.209 --> 00:24:46.151
see that most sites, they use them as a way to style the page or as a design tool rather than a semantic tool...

00:24:46.151 --> 00:24:46.918
Exactly,

00:24:46.918 --> 00:24:47.152
right?

00:24:47.152 --> 00:24:49.988
There's a lot to be said about active voice.

00:24:49.988 --> 00:24:55.393
There's a lot to be said about enhancements like table of contents, FAQ, key takeaways.

00:24:55.393 --> 00:25:01.166
I've seen that in my own usability study that we can talk a bit more about kind of the background context of that,

00:25:01.166 --> 00:25:06.571
but the people deliberately seek out these content elements

00:25:06.571 --> 00:25:09.774
as a way to skim and parse and anchor

00:25:09.774 --> 00:25:11.776
and essentially trying to find the answers, right?

00:25:11.776 --> 00:25:13.278
People don't have a lot of patience anymore.

00:25:13.278 --> 00:25:17.315
Maybe they never had, I don't know, but when they skim content, when they evaluate it

00:25:17.315 --> 00:25:22.420
they will look for these content elements so that they can say... Ah! okay, here's my answer

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:26.258
now that means that content is interesting

00:25:26.258 --> 00:25:28.126
now let me read it top to bottom, right?

00:25:28.126 --> 00:25:30.795
So it's this kind of like pyramid approach

00:25:30.795 --> 00:25:32.831
where you want to give the answer right away.

00:25:32.831 --> 00:25:34.432
So people just know, okay, my answer is here.

00:25:34.432 --> 00:25:36.301
it's worth for me spending time here.

00:25:36.301 --> 00:25:40.405
And then they might take time to read the rest of it. And all these content enhancements

00:25:40.405 --> 00:25:43.375
and structure and stuff also help significantly with that.

00:25:43.375 --> 00:25:47.712
And it helps bots who operate on a much simpler level to understand

00:25:47.712 --> 00:25:49.714
how this content relates to a larger topic.

00:25:49.714 --> 00:25:56.354
AI chatbots seem to be no different when it comes to that than search engines.

00:25:56.354 --> 00:26:00.392
You've written a lot about these guiding principles for web design.

00:26:00.392 --> 00:26:01.960
You just mentioned a few of them.

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:03.261
The ease of navigation.

00:26:03.261 --> 00:26:07.465
There's a lot of great examples like FAQs and summaries and highlights and stuff

00:26:07.465 --> 00:26:12.203
 that you've gone into really great depth on.

00:26:12.203 --> 00:26:13.538
And I appreciate it.

00:26:13.538 --> 00:26:18.510
Trust symbols is another piece that I think like you consider that a part of your website design.

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:21.646
That's a guiding principle now product pages, anything.

00:26:21.646 --> 00:26:27.319
The one thing I heard you say that I hadn't really heard is the importance of page speed

00:26:27.319 --> 00:26:29.654
being less important than we all thought.

00:26:29.654 --> 00:26:32.991
I think John and I produce a lot of, you know

00:26:32.991 --> 00:26:39.531
technical recommendations and a big part of our tech audits is typically how to improve page speed.

00:26:39.531 --> 00:26:43.134
It seems like it has just naturally become less of a priority.

00:26:43.134 --> 00:26:48.974
We always find more important things to address first, but we never lose sight of page speed.

00:26:48.974 --> 00:26:54.179
It seems like a new idea for me a little bit, it being less important.

00:26:54.179 --> 00:26:56.281
Yeah, you're right, Joe. Absolutely. It's a good observation.

00:26:56.281 --> 00:27:01.987
The way that I think about all of these recommendations and criteria is that it's very
contextual.

00:27:01.987 --> 00:27:06.691
 So most of what we talked about applies to blog content, right?

00:27:06.691 --> 00:27:11.363
But when we talk about maybe product or category pages, the focus can shift a little bit.

00:27:11.363 --> 00:27:15.567
And so in my experience with page speed and core web vitals

00:27:15.567 --> 00:27:17.202
I just group all of that together

00:27:17.202 --> 00:27:22.307
is that it's often, it gets a lot of attention because it's easy to measure, right?

00:27:22.307 --> 00:27:25.877
We get Search Console data, we can run tests and stuff.

00:27:25.877 --> 00:27:30.315
And so a lot of focus goes into that because we can see when the needle goes up or down.

00:27:30.315 --> 00:27:32.350
And I've had clients in,

00:27:32.350 --> 00:27:38.423
for example, the insurance space that have spent weeks on improving core web vitals with nothing to show for.

00:27:38.423 --> 00:27:43.261
And then I've had clients in e-commerce that have spent weeks improving core web vitals with a lot to show for.

00:27:43.261 --> 00:27:49.801
And so for me, the takeaway here is page speed, core web vitals, etc, matters the most when we're talking about

00:27:49.801 --> 00:27:57.575
transactional pages, product, category,  e-commerce stores, marketplaces, even right consumer marketplaces.

00:27:57.575 --> 00:28:01.846
That's when people have a transactional intent, page speed matters the most.

00:28:01.846 --> 00:28:06.951
And it scales specifically for e-commerce.

00:28:06.951 --> 00:28:11.389
It scales less when it comes to something like uh SaaS, right?

00:28:11.389 --> 00:28:18.763
So because you could argue, Oh, a SaaS landing page also has transaction intent, and that is true, but their page speed matters much less.

00:28:18.763 --> 00:28:26.037
When you are shopping, on the other hand, in e-commerce, and there's a lot of competition and low patience, right?

00:28:26.037 --> 00:28:31.376
If the page takes too long to load, you might just go to another store and buy a competitor product.

00:28:31.376 --> 00:28:33.812
And so that's where it's really critical.

00:28:33.812 --> 00:28:36.881
And I also see search engines reward that.

00:28:36.881 --> 00:28:45.023
And I'm not sure if search engines reward that because they measure page speed and the core vitals specifically

00:28:45.023 --> 00:28:49.994
or because they see that users prefer that page in the store because it loads faster.

00:28:49.994 --> 00:28:54.065
Now, there's one caveat to me, and that is time to first byte.

00:28:54.065 --> 00:29:00.805
Time to first byte or server response time, I think, is universally important for any site out there

00:29:00.805 --> 00:29:06.711
because it's so important that not just search engines, especially AI chatbots

00:29:06.711 --> 00:29:08.546
can crawl your site quickly.

00:29:08.546 --> 00:29:13.017
And not the page speed number that impacts scroll rate or speed,

00:29:13.017 --> 00:29:15.253
 the most is time to first byte.

00:29:15.253 --> 00:29:21.860
How long does it actually take the crawler to get the, I would say, raw HTML from your server.

00:29:21.860 --> 00:29:25.730
And so that is something that I'm keeping tabs on for all of my clients.

00:29:25.730 --> 00:29:31.569
Interesting. Yeah, we've you know, in core web vitals first came out, it was like, oh my God, we have to audit everything.

00:29:31.569 --> 00:29:37.208
I think now we're starting to understand that it isn't so binary, right?

00:29:37.208 --> 00:29:41.146
Like it does matter based on who the competition is.

00:29:41.146 --> 00:29:45.116
So, one way that we've approached is looking at it on a template level

00:29:45.116 --> 00:29:48.586
comparing a handful of searches against who we're competing with on page one.

00:29:48.586 --> 00:29:51.856
And if we see like really big discrepancies

00:29:51.856 --> 00:29:56.995
then we'll focus on the page template itself, not universally looking at the site.

00:29:56.995 --> 00:29:59.597
So that's helped us be a little bit smarter about

00:29:59.597 --> 00:30:03.568
advising clients on spending a ton of time here where you may not see,

00:30:03.568 --> 00:30:06.237
you know, the, output of it, like you mentioned.

00:30:06.237 --> 00:30:07.605
Smart.

00:30:07.639 --> 00:30:08.706
You mentioned the UX study.

00:30:08.706 --> 00:30:10.275
Maybe we can transition to that.

00:30:10.275 --> 00:30:13.344
I think that, being one of the first studies

00:30:13.344 --> 00:30:17.982
I thought I'd got a lot of great attention and there was a lot of great analysis and effort behind it.

00:30:17.982 --> 00:30:22.954
I think that, probably the most interesting thing to me was that there are still about

00:30:22.954 --> 00:30:27.859
I think, I think it was 80 % of users are still clicking after seeing the AIO.

00:30:27.859 --> 00:30:33.464
I don't know, was there anything else that was super insightful that you didn't expect to see from that study?

00:30:33.464 --> 00:30:35.533
Maybe just take us through some of those things.

00:30:35.533 --> 00:30:36.467
Man, so much.

00:30:36.467 --> 00:30:42.373
I would say it has significantly changed my view of SEO and maybe organic growth in general.

00:30:42.640 --> 00:30:46.477
For context, in March of this year

00:30:46.477 --> 00:30:52.650
together with a partner, named Eric Manbusker, he has experience with these types of usability studies

00:30:52.650 --> 00:30:55.253
He has done them for Backlinko and others.

00:30:55.253 --> 00:30:58.556
We conducted the first usability study of AI overviews.

00:30:58.556 --> 00:31:02.894
I was very unsatisfied with... look, I got a lot of access to aggregate data,

00:31:02.894 --> 00:31:07.232
so maybe it's a bit unfair for me to say, but I had this, like, big picture view. 

00:31:07.232 --> 00:31:14.072
The SimilarWeb analysis of like seven billion queries, like, you know, to understand what's going on in search results.

00:31:14.072 --> 00:31:17.542
Are people still clicking or not and zero clicks, all that kind of stuff.

00:31:17.542 --> 00:31:20.011
Incredibly helpful, but there was still a gap for me.

00:31:20.011 --> 00:31:26.651
And so, luckily I met Eric on a webinar and we caught up and Eric was like, hey, we should do something together.

00:31:26.784 --> 00:31:30.421
We riffed and then we came to this idea of this usability study.

00:31:30.421 --> 00:31:37.228
And what we did is we monitored and tracked the user behavior of 70 participants

00:31:37.228 --> 00:31:44.168
out of the US across different age ranges, across different devices in solving eight tasks.

00:31:44.469 --> 00:31:54.045
We gave them eight tasks like find a tax accountant in your area, find this e-commerce product, find this health information.

00:31:54.045 --> 00:31:55.747
And a lot of these

00:31:55.747 --> 00:32:01.052
but not all of those tasks were geared specifically for people to find AI overviews

00:32:01.052 --> 00:32:05.156
because we wanted to see how they engage with them without bias in them.

00:32:05.156 --> 00:32:08.526
So we didn't want to say, hey, if there's an AI overview, just engage with that.

00:32:08.526 --> 00:32:12.430
We wanted to just give them the task and then see how they naturally engage with it.

00:32:12.430 --> 00:32:14.799
And we got a ton of material out of it.

00:32:14.799 --> 00:32:17.101
I think it's an incredibly robust study.

00:32:17.101 --> 00:32:19.370
We had six people working on this.

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:20.772
It cost a lot of money.

00:32:20.772 --> 00:32:21.839
It took a lot of time.

00:32:21.839 --> 00:32:24.409
But the insights, I think, are very profound.

00:32:24.409 --> 00:32:26.377
And so the first one, you already mentioned it

00:32:26.377 --> 00:32:30.148
is that even though people click a lot
less

00:32:30.148 --> 00:32:34.152
and this is also validated by a lot of different research.

00:32:34.152 --> 00:32:38.823
For example, the study by Pew Research recently, which was also incredibly robust

00:32:38.823 --> 00:32:45.897
showing that 1 % of users click on a source or citation in AI overviews.

00:32:45.897 --> 00:32:48.299
That is just such a tiny number.

00:32:48.299 --> 00:32:49.667
Yeah. It's nothing.

00:32:49.667 --> 00:32:50.735
It’s just nothing.

00:32:50.735 --> 00:32:54.238
And it can explain also why these 1 % click at all.

00:32:54.238 --> 00:32:59.377
But yeah, it just goes to show that Google Search is going away from clicks, right?

00:32:59.377 --> 00:33:02.513
I hope that's pretty clear for everyone listening, right?

00:33:02.513 --> 00:33:05.383
Especially when you look at or think about AI mode.

00:33:05.383 --> 00:33:07.919
But search is not about clicks anymore, right?

00:33:07.919 --> 00:33:09.454
It's much more about answers and influence.

00:33:09.454 --> 00:33:15.093
But anyway, we saw that the clicks that are still going out, or let me put it this way.

00:33:15.093 --> 00:33:17.996
Clicks are a very noisy signal.

00:33:18.129 --> 00:33:19.330
A lot of clicks happen.

00:33:19.330 --> 00:33:20.798
And we saw this in this study.

00:33:20.798 --> 00:33:25.737
I put in the write-up of the study, I uploaded some clips of showing exactly that

00:33:25.737 --> 00:33:28.639
like how actual users behave and how they annotate and how they think.

00:33:28.639 --> 00:33:34.545
And so a lot of clicks are noisy because people click around to skim and scavenge.

00:33:34.545 --> 00:33:37.482
And a lot of clicks are not targeted and intentional.

00:33:37.482 --> 00:33:38.750
They're very impulsive.

00:33:38.750 --> 00:33:42.453
And people are searching and going back and forth and this and that.

00:33:42.453 --> 00:33:47.725
What we found is that a lot of the noise, these impulse clicks

00:33:47.725 --> 00:33:54.165
are going away when AI overviews are present because people get answers to the questions right away.

00:33:54.165 --> 00:33:59.404
And as a result, the clicks that they still do are much more intentional.

00:33:59.404 --> 00:34:00.671
And they click for a couple of reasons.

00:34:00.671 --> 00:34:02.640
One is to validate information from AI.

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:04.742
I'll come back to that in a second.

00:34:04.742 --> 00:34:07.478
And two, they click to take action.

00:34:07.478 --> 00:34:14.085
And so the revelation for me from the study is that there's this thing called a final click or what we called a final click

00:34:14.085 --> 00:34:15.987
which is basically the last click that people

00:34:15.987 --> 00:34:18.222
perform when they complete the user journey.

00:34:18.222 --> 00:34:25.029
And what we found that you addressed is that 80 % of these clicks are going to organic results, not to AI overviews.

00:34:25.029 --> 00:34:30.068
And it's aligned with this study from Pew Research because...

00:34:30.068 --> 00:34:38.543
People don't really click on citations, but they still click on organic results, much, much less than before AI overviews.

00:34:38.543 --> 00:34:43.047
But they do so to take action, like transact, find the information they're looking for,

00:34:43.047 --> 00:34:45.616
find the tax account, and etc, all this stuff that I mentioned before.

00:34:45.616 --> 00:34:49.387
So there's still a lot of value in organic results, but we cannot measure that value

00:34:49.387 --> 00:34:53.491
with clicks anymore, at least not to the same degree that we did before.

00:34:53.491 --> 00:34:57.728
Two, and I already mentioned this, people are validating AI results

00:34:57.728 --> 00:35:04.669
by going to platforms and communities like Reddit, YouTube, niche forums, LinkedIn, etc.

00:35:04.669 --> 00:35:10.274
So there is this new interesting user behavior that consists of trust and relevance.

00:35:10.274 --> 00:35:15.113
So it seems like before AI overviews, people predominantly judged the search results by relevance.

00:35:15.113 --> 00:35:16.681
Does it answer my question?

00:35:16.681 --> 00:35:20.051
Now, people first look at the...

00:35:20.051 --> 00:35:24.088
domain, the citation, the brand, and they ask themselves, do I know this?

00:35:24.088 --> 00:35:26.390
Do I know this and trust this?

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:29.794
And when they do, then they apply the relevance check.

00:35:29.794 --> 00:35:31.996
So then they ask themselves, uh can this answer my question?

00:35:31.996 --> 00:35:37.001
And as a result, it means that, first of all, we need to be focusing much more on these other platforms

00:35:37.001 --> 00:35:41.939
because that's where people gain and build trust into brands and results.

00:35:41.939 --> 00:35:49.247
But second, also means that ideally we have a preconceived notion in the minds of our users before they search.

00:35:49.247 --> 00:35:50.314
What does it mean?

00:35:50.314 --> 00:35:56.120
They should ideally have heard of us or know us and even better in a positive sentiment.

00:35:56.120 --> 00:36:03.327
And so some of that can come from people having visited our site previously, but you get into this chicken egg problem, right?

00:36:03.327 --> 00:36:08.933
Where it's like, you need trust for people to click on your site and you want to build trust when people are on your site.

00:36:08.933 --> 00:36:09.934
So where do you start?

00:36:09.934 --> 00:36:10.434
Right.

00:36:10.434 --> 00:36:16.007
I think a lot of that goes into advertising and maybe collaborations and other ways to get in front of users.

00:36:16.007 --> 00:36:22.680
But that is becoming so much more important because if people don't trust and have heard of you, then you're mostly invisible, right?

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:29.520
Unless we're talking about like utility utility, like they're just trying to find the cheapest product then these filters fall away much more.

00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:31.822
But a lot of other cases, they very much apply.

00:36:31.822 --> 00:36:35.026
And the last thing I'll say is there's also a big age difference.

00:36:35.026 --> 00:36:41.532
I found that older users are much less receptive to AI answers.

00:36:41.532 --> 00:36:43.701
They're much more likely to skip them all together.

00:36:43.701 --> 00:36:50.942
Whereas younger users are very receptive and they don't look at the organic search results nearly as much as older cohorts.

00:36:50.942 --> 00:36:53.511
So there is that age part as well.

00:36:53.544 --> 00:36:59.650
Can I, I wanna try to paraphrase, maybe summarize one of the big points that I heard.

00:36:59.650 --> 00:37:03.955
I've heard you say this in different ways with different people

00:37:03.955 --> 00:37:06.224
and you've written about it a little bit differently too.

00:37:06.224 --> 00:37:12.263
Just for that older cohort that doesn't trust the AI overview as much as the younger cohort,

00:37:12.263 --> 00:37:18.669
it seemed like your usability study showed that older cohort would scroll down to

00:37:18.669 --> 00:37:24.442
organic results to verify, maybe not clicking in to the organic results,

00:37:24.442 --> 00:37:31.115
but at least using that first set of organic rankings to build some trust

00:37:31.115 --> 00:37:33.384
 in what they saw in the AI overview.

00:37:33.384 --> 00:37:36.220
And for me, that is a...

00:37:36.220 --> 00:37:39.457
That's an indication that rankings still matter.

00:37:39.457 --> 00:37:46.197
We've been talking a little bit about rankings mattering less and measuring search SEO success

00:37:46.197 --> 00:37:50.134
with clicks matters less, but it still feels like you want to rank well

00:37:50.134 --> 00:37:52.970
organically to build trust.

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:54.438
Yes, that is absolutely right.

00:37:54.438 --> 00:37:56.674
You want to rank organically to build trust.

00:37:56.674 --> 00:38:01.612
And you also want to rank organically so that Google pulls you into the AI overviews.

00:38:01.612 --> 00:38:03.180
And yes, people click a lot less.

00:38:03.180 --> 00:38:06.884
And at the same time, Google still plays around with the format a lot.

00:38:06.884 --> 00:38:12.089
They start to show a lot more links, fragments or parts of the answer.

00:38:12.089 --> 00:38:14.325
They highlight brands in the answer.

00:38:14.325 --> 00:38:16.160
So, you are correct.

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:18.095
Organic ranks still matter.

00:38:18.095 --> 00:38:23.067
What is changing and becoming more important also is this whole kind of idea

00:38:23.067 --> 00:38:24.802
of covering many user intents

00:38:24.802 --> 00:38:28.439
which directly relates or alludes to query fan out.

00:38:28.439 --> 00:38:33.077
So another big topic right now is query fan out, not just in the AI mode

00:38:33.077 --> 00:38:36.547
but also in ChatGTP and Perplexity all use query fan out technology.

00:38:36.547 --> 00:38:44.855
And in a nutshell, it's about these AI is trying to cover and include different user intents.

00:38:44.855 --> 00:38:50.761
Rankings are important and also clustering them by topic and by user intent

00:38:50.761 --> 00:38:53.998
filling these gaps even more important as well.

00:38:53.998 --> 00:38:57.601
I want to dig into that in a second, but you mentioned

00:38:57.601 --> 00:39:01.205
this study really having an impact on sort of how you think about SEO.

00:39:01.205 --> 00:39:07.011
Was that purely from a traffic driving perspective, or were there actual tactics

00:39:07.011 --> 00:39:10.948
or I don't know, methodologies that you

00:39:10.948 --> 00:39:14.418
maybe decided weren't as important as what you saw in the past?

00:39:14.418 --> 00:39:15.619
It’s a good question.

00:39:15.619 --> 00:39:21.425
I definitely got a new found love again for these, like content features

00:39:21.425 --> 00:39:25.663
because we saw so many people who you know they were looking for information they quickly go to

00:39:25.663 --> 00:39:29.300
 a site like US News and they have this box with key takeaways

00:39:29.300 --> 00:39:33.504
and like oh yeah that's what I'm looking for right, so that kind of motion came up a lot

00:39:33.504 --> 00:39:35.940
trust and authority came up a lot and so

00:39:35.940 --> 00:39:39.377
for me it for example put into perspective the Google Quality Rater guidelines

00:39:39.377 --> 00:39:43.347
which also say that trust is the most important factor when it comes to EAT.

00:39:43.347 --> 00:39:47.818
just basically, like this study helped me understand what EAT is in general.

00:39:47.818 --> 00:39:51.555
It's just, it's really a framework for how users evaluate search results.

00:39:51.555 --> 00:39:57.495
And that's why Google wants to double kind of verify that with humans,

00:39:57.495 --> 00:40:01.232
or basically verify their search results with humans.

00:40:01.232 --> 00:40:05.002
But it was like, what's less important, it's hard to say, you know, I mean,

00:40:05.002 --> 00:40:09.373
backlinks that's always kind of a big question like how important are they still

00:40:09.373 --> 00:40:13.978
and I haven't come to a definitive answer especially now in this new AI search world.

00:40:13.978 --> 00:40:17.748
Speed was not really a factor in those studies

00:40:17.748 --> 00:40:22.453
So it's hard for me to pinpoint something that has become less important.

00:40:22.453 --> 00:40:27.491
I think it just re-ranked my set of things to pay attention to.

00:40:27.491 --> 00:40:28.926
Yeah, you mentioned link building.

00:40:28.926 --> 00:40:31.562
How do you talk to clients about link building in today's world?

00:40:31.562 --> 00:40:34.432
Like, certainly you work with some brands that...

00:40:34.432 --> 00:40:37.835
I remember when Joe and I were at Razorfish, was always fun to work with those brands

00:40:37.835 --> 00:40:40.104
because you didn't always need to worry about link building.

00:40:40.104 --> 00:40:44.675
They were just so strong and you could do something very simple and see a great impact.

00:40:44.675 --> 00:40:49.046
But you also work with a lot of companies who are just sort of starting, right?

00:40:49.046 --> 00:40:53.117
So they don't necessarily have that domain authority and link building must come up

00:40:53.117 --> 00:40:55.853
I would imagine, in your conversations when you're advising.

00:40:55.853 --> 00:40:58.622
So how do you talk to them about

00:40:58.622 --> 00:41:01.792
link building is link buying ever an option?

00:41:01.792 --> 00:41:03.360
Is it a PR push?

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:04.762
Yeah, just curious about that.

00:41:04.762 --> 00:41:09.667
It's still a big conversation point, because you're absolutely right.

00:41:09.667 --> 00:41:11.502
There are some companies that still need links.

00:41:11.502 --> 00:41:16.407
For example, on the local search level, that is still very much a thing.

00:41:16.407 --> 00:41:20.711
And there's a whole machinery behind it that still works like maybe 10 years ago

00:41:20.711 --> 00:41:26.851
or 20 years ago, where you buy links from the publishers or affiliate sites,

00:41:26.851 --> 00:41:28.586
and they do have an impact.

00:41:28.586 --> 00:41:32.456
But then, as you also said, there are these other large brands where link building

00:41:32.456 --> 00:41:37.461
is basically PR, and it's much more about being mentioned and the sentiment and the

00:41:37.461 --> 00:41:40.598
perception you create rather than hard backlinks.

00:41:40.598 --> 00:41:44.602
For me, I'm still investigating this much, much deeper, but it does seem like

00:41:44.602 --> 00:41:47.071
I mean, from the early data that I pulled, backlinks are much less important.

00:41:47.071 --> 00:41:48.739
The volume of backlinks doesn't matter.

00:41:48.739 --> 00:41:52.710
The quality is still something that I'm circling around for AI search.

00:41:52.710 --> 00:41:54.311
And then it's all very contextual, right?

00:41:54.311 --> 00:41:56.280
I think you can see this in a lot of websites

00:41:56.280 --> 00:41:59.717
that were historically very strong when it comes to links

00:41:59.717 --> 00:42:04.722
I have the feeling that Google just devalued backlinks as a signal significantly.

00:42:04.722 --> 00:42:09.627
And the value of the content, the engagement, all that kind of stuff has taken a lot of that place.

00:42:09.627 --> 00:42:15.132
So the backlink conversations with my clients are a lot more around, again, the unique data 

00:42:15.132 --> 00:42:19.503
PR, like how do we create narratives, support them with data, and then amplify them

00:42:19.503 --> 00:42:22.940
in a way that gets us in front of the audience and creates like a really good...

00:42:22.940 --> 00:42:25.142
 the perception that we want.

00:42:25.142 --> 00:42:27.645
Yeah, there's still some questions.

00:42:27.645 --> 00:42:32.783
And at the same time, though, I think a lot of the focus switches from backlinks to mentions.

00:42:32.783 --> 00:42:36.887
And that is a slightly different game, but also a completely different game, right?

00:42:36.887 --> 00:42:40.157
You still have, like a lot of companies still do outreach for mentions.

00:42:40.157 --> 00:42:44.461
Not sure how successful that is, but big brands, they think much more about stuff like

00:42:44.461 --> 00:42:49.667
hey, should we give a site like NerdWallet or Forbes or others, should we give them a couple

00:42:49.667 --> 00:42:56.907
of 10,000s of dollars so that we get an advertorial or that we get featured by them and
then we get a backlink and a mention or not?

00:42:56.907 --> 00:43:00.177
Those are much more the dimensions where, again, local players are like

00:43:00.177 --> 00:43:04.782
should I spend 500 bucks on getting 50 links across these like...

00:43:04.949 --> 00:43:08.852
local publishers, it's just very different dimensions.

00:43:08.852 --> 00:43:11.121
And again, the impact is also very different.

00:43:11.121 --> 00:43:15.125
Well, the trade-off is using the NerdWallet example, right?

00:43:15.125 --> 00:43:17.995
If I could pay an amount and be visible

00:43:17.995 --> 00:43:21.532
like they've done all the work to rank for some
of these really competitive terms

00:43:21.532 --> 00:43:26.270
if I can just pay and be there tomorrow, versus having

00:43:26.270 --> 00:43:29.239
to build out a plan, creating the content, right?

00:43:29.239 --> 00:43:33.444
Like this massive effort behind the scenes, especially for a smaller brand.

00:43:33.444 --> 00:43:37.681
You know, if you do that calculation, oftentimes it makes more sense to just be there.

00:43:37.681 --> 00:43:42.620
We worked with a bank who had a really strong, checking bonus offer

00:43:42.620 --> 00:43:47.157
and for what it would have taken them to rank for, you know

00:43:47.157 --> 00:43:50.527
the nerd wallet content would have been monumental.

00:43:50.527 --> 00:43:54.298
But they got into the affiliate program and they saw tons and tons of success

00:43:54.298 --> 00:43:56.800
from that for, you know, basically a fixed fee.

00:43:56.800 --> 00:43:58.535
So for them, it made a lot of sense.

00:43:58.535 --> 00:44:03.574
I want to talk, we've talked a lot about shifting traffic and, you know, measurement.

00:44:03.574 --> 00:44:09.213
You had this great post on LinkedIn around like the new KPIs for AI driven search.

00:44:09.213 --> 00:44:15.586
Things like measuring how influential an impression would be, share a voice, those
sorts of things.

00:44:15.586 --> 00:44:18.455
Brand recall and trust, which we've talked a lot about.

00:44:18.455 --> 00:44:22.860
How do you, again, in your sort of advisor role.

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:26.864
how do you help your sort of client

00:44:26.864 --> 00:44:34.071
take these changing KPIs and sort of train the board or train the CEO on like how to

00:44:34.071 --> 00:44:37.608
think differently about what SEO's value is

00:44:37.608 --> 00:44:39.476
or what organic traffic's value is?

00:44:39.476 --> 00:44:43.747
I think this is the conversation Joe and I are starting to tease a little bit.

00:44:43.847 --> 00:44:46.417
And some of the reception is like, it makes total sense.

00:44:46.417 --> 00:44:51.822
Others are like, well, you know, I still want to know where I rank for X keyword.

00:44:51.822 --> 00:44:52.589
So I'd love to get a little bit of a sense on how you're, how you're thinking about that.

00:44:52.589 --> 00:44:55.726
So I'd love to get a little bit of a sense on how you're, how you're thinking about that.

00:44:55.726 --> 00:45:00.097
It's a very timely question because I have that conversation with almost all of my clients.

00:45:00.097 --> 00:45:07.638
The goal is to drive more towards leading indicators like ranks, visibility, share of voice

00:45:07.638 --> 00:45:12.676
then lagging indicators like impressions and revenue impact.

00:45:12.676 --> 00:45:14.078
But it's very challenging.

00:45:14.078 --> 00:45:16.013
It's very, very challenging because...

00:45:16.013 --> 00:45:21.752
It's a big pitch and leadership loses a lot of control because clicks were such a good

00:45:21.752 --> 00:45:24.988
intermediary with this classic search funnel.

00:45:24.988 --> 00:45:27.257
You had the search, click, convert.

00:45:27.257 --> 00:45:28.459
Makes perfect sense.

00:45:28.459 --> 00:45:33.764
Now it's like search, read a lot, be influenced, and at some point come to the home page
and sign up.

00:45:33.764 --> 00:45:38.102
It's a very disjointed broken funnel and accepting that is hard for leadership.

00:45:38.102 --> 00:45:40.504
It's a slow transition.

00:45:40.504 --> 00:45:50.347
And there are more leading indicators that I'm developing with my clients as a result to
give a sense of control, right?.

00:45:50.347 --> 00:45:55.586
And look like, you know, there can also be... There's also a bigger focus on input.

00:45:55.586 --> 00:45:59.323
What are we actually doing to drive the needle, remove the needle?

00:45:59.323 --> 00:46:01.125
Are we meeting our targets in that sense?

00:46:01.125 --> 00:46:03.794
And then down the line, what's the downstream impact?

00:46:03.794 --> 00:46:05.229
What's the output?

00:46:05.229 --> 00:46:09.500
And also in lot of cases, it takes like a test or transition period

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:13.771
because the reality is that things can still change very quickly.

00:46:13.771 --> 00:46:18.742
Don't forget, it's been about two and a half, a bit more, maybe two and three quarters 

00:46:18.742 --> 00:46:23.814
years since ChatGPT 3 came out and changed a lot.

00:46:23.814 --> 00:46:29.520
And then it's been about a year, maybe a bit more since AI overviews launched

00:46:29.520 --> 00:46:31.488
and the big impact really just came this year.

00:46:31.488 --> 00:46:33.323
So all of this is very fresh and new.

00:46:33.323 --> 00:46:37.261
And it's very hard to then say, OK, ah yesterday we saw this change.

00:46:37.261 --> 00:46:39.363
Today we're developing this new model of metrics.

00:46:39.363 --> 00:46:42.666
And tomorrow we're going to just stick to that.

00:46:42.666 --> 00:46:43.934
Things are going to change again.

00:46:43.934 --> 00:46:46.136
And that creates lot of uncertainty and mistrust from leadership.

00:46:46.136 --> 00:46:48.772
And that creates lot of uncertainty and mistrust from leadership.

00:46:48.772 --> 00:46:52.776
We're doing things like, again, measuring some of these leading and lagging indicators.

00:46:52.776 --> 00:46:56.580
We're trying to get more qualitative data from brand surveys,

00:46:56.580 --> 00:47:01.084
from user, market research, user interviews, all these kind of things.

00:47:01.084 --> 00:47:03.687
And then of course the big question is always like what comes out on the other end

00:47:03.687 --> 00:47:06.423
like what's the bottom line and that's the anchor point for leadership.

00:47:06.423 --> 00:47:09.393
That's what gives them more security, and shows them that as an as a team.

00:47:09.393 --> 00:47:13.130
We're not we don't want to move away from company impact, right?

